            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Timur Alavi\u2019s day begins not with an alarm, but with the distant, familiar groan of the N-Judah Muni train. It\u2019s the soundtrack to his life in the Inner Richmond, a life he built deliberately, mile by mile, away from the quiet suburbs of his youth. The son of Iranian immigrants who settled in Irvine, California, Timur was raised on a steady diet of sacrifice, expectation, and the importance of a stable career. His parents, a pharmacist and an engineer, saw his Bachelor\u2019s in Business Administration as the fulfillment of their American dream\u2014a secure, respectable path.\n\nTimur followed that path diligently. He excelled at UC Irvine, landed a coveted internship, and upon graduation, accepted the Assistant Buyer position with a major retailer headquartered in downtown San Francisco. It was his ticket to independence and to a city that pulsed with an energy Irvine never had. He embraced the routine: the 5.5-mile commute spent listening to business podcasts, the days lost in spreadsheets analyzing sales data, and the evenings spent with his two roommates in their rent-controlled apartment.\n\nThe turning point wasn't a single event, but a slow-dawning realization. While he was good at predicting what mainstream consumers would buy next season, he felt creatively starved. His job was about margins and units, not story or soul. His true passion surfaces on weekends. He explores the Mission\u2019s craft markets, studies the curated aesthetics of small Hayes Valley boutiques, and sketches designs in his notebook at a foggy cafe near Golden Gate Park.\n\nSocially, he has a tight-knit circle of friends\u2014a mix from college and work\u2014who are his chosen family. They are his companions for cheap eats on Clement Street, pickup soccer games at Beach Chalet, and navigating the complexities of their mid-twenties.\n\nTimur's dream is beginning to take shape. He envisions a small, independent shop of his own one day. It would fuse his sharp business acumen with his heritage\u2014a space featuring modern menswear alongside curated goods from artisans in Iran and across Central Asia. For now, he saves aggressively, learns an enormous amount about supply chains, and considers San Francisco his incubator. He\u2019s playing the long game, using his stable job as the foundation to build something that is truly his own."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers that first solo ride on the N-Judah, just after unpacking. Squeezed between a student and a chef, he watched the city unfold\u2014Duboce Triangle, Cole Valley, the Avenues. The groan of the train wasn\u2019t noise; it was the city's heartbeat. He felt a profound, electric thrill of independence, a feeling Irvine could never offer. It was the moment San Francisco stopped being a destination and became his home. This happened his first week in the city, confirming he\u2019d made the right choice.\n\n2.\nIt was a Tuesday night, well past 8 PM, during his second year at the company. Staring at a spreadsheet for 50,000 beige acrylic sweaters, he felt a hollow ache. The numbers were perfect, the margins were great, but there was no story, no soul. He wasn\u2019t creating anything, just feeding a machine. That night, the creative starvation he\u2019d felt became a sharp, undeniable pain. It was the night he decided his career couldn't just be about units sold; it had to mean something more.\n\n3.\nHe was wandering a Mission craft market last spring when he saw it: a small, hand-dyed kilim with a geometric pattern that mirrored one on a pillow in his grandmother\u2019s home. He spoke to the vendor, his heart racing. In that moment, his vague dream crystallized. It wasn\u2019t just about making clothes; it was about connecting threads\u2014from modern SF to ancient Persia. The shop wasn\u2019t a fantasy anymore; it was a future he could build. He bought the textile; it now hangs above his desk.\n\n4.\nLast winter, after losing a promotion he'd worked months for, he felt adrift. He texted his roommates, and within an hour, they were all crowded into a tiny spot on Clement Street, steam from soup dumplings fogging the windows. No one offered platitudes. They just shared food, told bad jokes, and were present. He realized then that his true safety net wasn't a job title, but these people. This was his chosen family, and in San Francisco, that was everything.\n\n5.\nOn a foggy Saturday a few months ago, sitting in his favorite cafe, he finalized his first deal. It was a tiny order\u2014three hand-stitched leather wallets from an artisan in Shiraz, negotiated over a crackly WhatsApp call. No one in the cafe knew. But as he transferred the money, a quiet, powerful sense of accomplishment washed over him. He wasn't just an assistant buyer anymore. He was building his supply chain, piece by piece, fulfilling a promise to himself."
